# Security Standards (Healthcare)

## PII & Health Data
- **Never** log patient names, fiscal codes, diagnoses, or any health-related data
- **Never** expose PII in error messages or API responses beyond what's needed
- Encrypt sensitive fields at rest (DB or application-layer encryption)
- Keys managed via secret manager / secure environment configuration

## Authorization
- Every protected Flask endpoint must enforce authn + authz checks
- Use explicit policy checks in route/service layer when conditional logic exists
- Scope queries by current user permissions; avoid unconstrained access to records

## Input Validation
- Always validate input with request schemas (Pydantic/Marshmallow)
- Separate schema constraints for create vs update when fields differ
- Reject unknown fields for sensitive endpoints unless explicitly allowed

## SQL Injection Prevention
- Use parameterized queries, ActiveRecord scopes, or Arel
- Never interpolate user input into SQL strings

## CSRF
- Cookie-based auth flows require CSRF protection
- Token-based APIs should disable CSRF and rely on strict auth headers
- Webhooks must verify signatures before processing payloads

## Dependency Security
- Run Python dependency scans before each release (`pip-audit` / `safety`)
- Run frontend scans (`npm audit` or equivalent)
- Include SAST in CI (Bandit for Python + Semgrep/CodeQL where available)

## Secrets
- All secrets via secure env vars or secret manager
- Never commit `.env`, credentials JSON, private keys, or tokens
